    "A New and Concise Bible Dictionary": "The `[group_Canaanites_Gen_10]` word is translated 'divine' in 2 Peter `[char_Peter_Mat_4]` 1: 3, 4. 2. \u03b8\u03b5\u03b9 \u1f79 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2, that which is characteristic of God, namely, 'divinity.' Rom. 1: 20. 3. \u03b8\u03b5 \u1f79 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2, Deity or Godhead; in Christ 'dwells all the fulness of the Godhead bodily.' Col. 2:\n29. Ramoth Gilead. [Ra'moth Gil'ead] Fortified city on the east of the Jordan and south of the Jabbok, in the tribe of Gad. It was one of Solomon `[char_Solomon_Ref]`'s strongholds, but it afterwards fell into the hands of the Syrians. Ahab lost his life in trying to recover it. Joram was successful in taking it, but was wounded by the Syrians. We do not read of it later. 1 Kings 4: 13; 1 Kings 22: 4-29; 2 Kings 8: 28; 2 Kings 9: 1-14; 2 Chr. 18: 2-28; 2 Chr. 22:\n29. The soul thus has, outside of circumstances here, a portion unaffected by circumstances, and that satisfies all its longings. On the other hand there is no rest to the wicked, who are like the troubled waves of the sea; and those who bow to the future imperial beast and his image will have no rest from their torments day nor night for ever and ever. Isa. 57: 20, 21; Rev. 14:\n29. Shealtiel. [Sheal'tiel] See SALATHIEL. Sheariah. [Sheari'ah] Son of Azel, a Benjamite. 1 Chr. 8: 38; 1 Chr. 9:",
    "Dr. Peter S. Ruckman": "These English Reformation nuggets, carefully concealed in the 1611 text, were overlooked by the commentators altogether. There are no 2,000 commentators who ever observed these three inspired (and preserved) peculiarities of the Reformation Text. With [v_Jhn_1_1] John `[char_John_Ref]` 1:1\u20132 staring them right in the face in Proverbs 30:5, the men who talk so much about \u201cChrist being the final authority, not the King James Bible\u201d overlook Him and ignore Him. This is quite typical of a lot of \u201cFundamentalism\u201d today, especially among the ranks of those who have been snared by the \u201cfear of man\u201d (see [v_Pro_29_25] Prov. 29:25) and nearly have a heart attack when a \u201cChristian\u201d infidel mentions \u201cBibliolatry.\u201d \u201cWho hath ascended?\u201d No man hath ascended [v_Jhn_3_13] (John `[char_John_Ref]` 3:13) except the Word of God mentioned in the next verse. Moses `[char_Moses_Exo_2]` was taken up; Elijah was caught up; Enoch was translated; but the word \u201cascend\u201d (John `[char_John_Ref]` 20:17) means to go up \u201cunder your own power.\u201d The only [v_Isa_14_13] men who ever tried this outside of Satan (Isa. 14:13) were the rocket scientists of the twentieth century. None will [v_Pro_30_4] make it. The \u201cheaven\u201d of Proverbs 30:4 is the heaven of [v_Isa_14_12] Isaiah `[char_Isaiah_Gen_26]` 14:12\u201313; and if God gave mankind 2,000 more years to \u201cachieve racial harmony,\u201d \u201cbring in peace on earth,\u201d etc. (and man has less than forty years left!!), and get to Venus, he would never reach the third heaven of 2 Corinthians 12:1\u2013",
    "Commentary Vol. 83": "And Jacob `[char_Jacob_Ref]` sod pottage, etc.] Or boiled broth; this he did at a certain time, for this was not his usual employment; the Targum of Jonathan says, it was on the day in which Abraham `[char_Abraham_Exo_17]` died; and whereas this [v_Gen_25_34] pottage was made of lentiles, as appears from (<012534>Genesis 25:34); this the Jewish writers f1400 say was the food of mourners; and so this circumstance furnishes out a reason for Jacob `[char_Jacob_Ref]`\u2019s boiling pottage of lentiles at this time: and hence also they f1401 gather, that Jacob `[char_Jacob_Ref]` and Esau `[char_Esau_Gen_25]` were now fifteen years of age; for Abraham `[char_Abraham_Exo_17]` was an hundred years old when Isaac was born, and Isaac was sixty at the birth of his sons; and Abraham `[char_Abraham_Exo_17]` lived to be one hundred and seventy five, and therefore Esau `[char_Esau_Gen_25]` and Jacob `[char_Jacob_Ref]` must be fifteen years old when he died: and Esau `[char_Esau_Gen_25]` came from the field, and be [was] faint: for want of food, and weary with hunting, and perhaps more so, having toiled and got nothing. 462\nVer.\n29. Man's duties in the garden?\n29. Cite Isaiah `[char_Isaiah_Gen_26]`'s comparison of man's stupidity with the intelligence of the beasts."
