    "Ruckman, Dr. Peter S_": "The remainder are called \u201cthe unjust,\u201d the \u201cdead,\u201d and \u201cthe wicked,\u201d and they DO NOT RISE. They are RAISED to face [v_Dan_12_2] condemnation (see Dan. 12:2; Luke 14:14; 1 Pet. 4:5; Rev. 20:5). These two groups are so clearly marked and so clearly divided that 1,000 years separates their place and time of judgment. No man who ever \u201cstudied to show himself approved unto God\u201d ever failed to \u201cRIGHTLY DIVIDE\u201d at this point. But Augustine, Origen, Eusebius, Jerome, Irenaeus, Calvin, Berkhof, Hodge, Strong, and the popes fail to attain these rudiments of freshman Bible study. All teach a general resurrection and a general judgment, thus contradicting the teaching of Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` Christ, and demonstrating conclusively that they are brethren of the Sadducees. They too \u201cdo greatly err, not knowing the Scripture!\u201d \u201cAnd when the multitude heard this, they were astonished at his doctrine.\u201d One can easily understand why they were. The multitude of A.D. 33, as the multitude of 1962, was a group of Bible ignoramuses, and from their blind beggars to their long-robed priests, they were all in the dark. Like the fanatical Catholic newspaper reporters at the ecumenical council of Pope John `[char_John_Ref]` (1962), who knelt and slobbered and wept when the old wine-head \u201cblessed them,\u201d the multitude knew nothing about Bible doctrine except the leaven of the Pharisees and Sadducees\u2014rabbinical tradition. 22:34 But when the Pharisees had heard that he had put the Sadducees to silence, they were gathered together. 35 Then one of them, which was a lawyer, asked him a question, tempting him, and saying, 36 Master, which is the great commandment in the law? 37 Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` said unto him, Thou shalt love the Lord thy God with all thy heart, and with all thy soul, and with all thy mind. 38 This is the first and great commandment. 39 And the second is like unto it, Thou shalt love thy neighbour as thyself. 40 On these two commandments hang all the law and the prophets. Mark prepares the reader for the scene by adding that \u201cone of the scribes came, and having heard them reasoning together, and perceiving that he had answered them well, asked him....\u201d The last of the \u201cbig four\u201d shows up. Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` has shut the Herodians up on the Tribute question. He has shut up the Sadducees on the Resurrection question. He shut up the Pharisees (who were priests) [v_Mat_21_45] in Matthew 21:45 on the Baptism question, and now a scribe, who is a LAWYER, sallies forth. However, the reader should notice that the lawyer has a double motive. He is not only \u201csicked on\u201d to the Lord Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`, but he has some semblance of honesty about him for we read, \u201chaving heard...and perceiving that he had answered them well.\u201d This man, with an ear for legal logic, is not altogether a hypocrite. Secretly he admires any man who can stand trial and answer the way Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` has been doing. But still the \u201ctempting him\u201d shows that the motive is double. He admires Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`, but he still wants to test His mettle. \u201cWhich is the great commandment?\u201d Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` answers with the [v_Exo_20_1] first commandment, but the answer is not from Exodus 20:1\u20133; it is [v_Deu_6_5] from Deuteronomy 6:\n20. CHAPTER 23 23:1 Then spake Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` to the multitude, and to his disciples, 2 Saying, The scribes and the Pharisees sit in Moses `[char_Moses_Exo_2]`\u2019 seat: 3 All therefore whatsoever they bid you observe, that observe and do; but do not ye after their works: for they say, and do not. 4 For they bind heavy burdens and grievous to be borne, and lay them on men\u2019s shoulders; but they themselves will not move them with one of their fingers. 5 But all their works they do for to be seen of men: they make broad their phylacteries, and enlarge the borders of their garments, 6 And love the uppermost rooms at feasts, and the chief seats in the synagogues, 7 And greetings in the markets, and to be called of men, Rabbi, Rabbi. \u201cSit in Moses `[char_Moses_Exo_2]`\u2019 seat.\u201d The phrase is indicative of what has taken place since Moses `[char_Moses_Exo_2]` no longer \u201csat all day to judge the people\u201d [v_Exo_18_13] (Exod. 18:13\u201314). The long-robed \u201cfathers\u201d (see Matt. 23:9) had usurped the legislative powers given to the prophet and deliverer of Israel and had seated themselves in the place of power, to give a variety of \u201cex cathedra\u201d (out-of-the-seat!) utterances. These Talmudic commentaries and interpretations on the Scripture were superimposed (as they are today) to obscure the fulfillment of prophecies that dealt with the coming Messiah. [A short conversation with any educated rabbi in the 1960\u2019s will bring this truth into clear view. This \u201cex cathedra\u201d business of course is better known to the American and European as the \u201cinfallible decrees\u201d and \u201cpapal bulls\u201d of various wineheads in Rome who usurp the authority of the Holy Spirit in pretending to be the true \u201cpillar and ground of truth.\u201d Giving credit where credit is due, the Catholic might be interested to know that there have been dozens of church fights and schisms and splits in the papacy: 241 priests in England (in 1870) denied the council\u2019s doctrine on papal utterances; eight archbishops and thirty bishops in France said it was absolutely out of reason, and forty-five German and Austrian bishops and five archbishops said the same. Seven ITALIAN bishops turned thumbs down on it (!), as well as a cardinal from Vienna, Austria (Peterson, Rise and Fall of the RCC, pp. 65, 33, 76, 87, and 257).] We should always keep clearly in mind that Rome has never had a consistent creed or doctrine and has never had a Biblical doctrine of salvation or prophecy. Constantly changing, she is never the same, and only the skeleton outline of the catechism remains the same, on paper. This, too, changes remarkably (in practice) from year to year. As Rome\u2019s main propaganda periodical, Life magazine, has so aptly stated, \u201cThe council has vast powers to bring about, with papal approval, sweeping revisions of both church laws and administration\u201d (Life, Oct. 12, 1962). This is good Catholic \u201cdoctrine.\u201d That is, at any time, under any political expedient, it can always change anything it wants to change anytime it wants to change it, irregardless of what the Bible may have to say about it. (\u201cEx cathedra\u201d merely means that if it is desirable to correct, revise, alter, change, or cancel the word of God, it can be done by pretending that someone is authorized by the word of God to do it! Some more nice folks.) \u201cAll therefore whatsoever they bid you observe....\u201d At this point Bullinger has come forth with an exegesis which may allow some examination. He reads, \u201cTherefore, whatsoever they bid you observe, that you observe and do; but do not...!\u201d Bullinger deduces that since what follows (vss. 4\u201331) clearly warns them not to do what the Pharisees do, that Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` could not be telling them in\n20. The time and place becomes the end of the Tribulation, exactly as it is found in every place in Matthew 24\u2013",
